<td tEditID="c1r1" style=" background-color:#FFFFFF; bEditID:r3st1; color:#000000; bLabel:main; font-size:12pt; font-family:arial;" aEditID="c1r1" locked="0" >
<![CDATA[<div style="text-align: right;"><div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><div style="font-family: arial; font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-align: left;"><font class="Apple-style-span" style="" size="2" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="border-spacing: 5px;"><br></span></font></div><div style="text-align: left;"><font class="Apple-style-span" style="" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><span class="Apple-style-span" style="border-spacing: 5px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Dear&nbsp;{!Contact.Salutation} {!Contact.LastName},</span></font></div><span lang="en-GB" style="text-align: start; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><div style="margin: 0px;"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">Eleanor Roosevelt famously declared that, “the future belongs to those who believe in the beauty of their dreams”. &nbsp;As a school, we are lucky that this is our core business: enabling children and young men and women to dream big, and equipping them with the skills, knowledge, personal qualities and characteristics that will enable them to achieve those dreams.</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">This week, Mr Mycroft, our newly appointed Head of Key Stage 5, has started to meet with all our Year 11 students to talk with them about their hopes and dreams for the future. &nbsp;This is the first step in helping to guide them through the choices and decisions that lie ahead as they move towards their A Levels and university course selections. &nbsp;Later this term we will have a visit from a college counsellor to help further refine students’ thinking and to talk to parents about the global Higher Education landscape. &nbsp;I will then meet with all the Year 11s before they make their final A Level choices.</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">At the other end of the school, my thanks go to the staff in Primary who have demonstrated excellent teamwork in supporting absent colleagues’ classes and ensuring that the children’s days are full of learning and fun.</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">In regards to staff absence, please be aware that in Primary, we are continuing with the policy followed by Mr Harvey over the past few years. &nbsp;We inform parents of any absence which continues for more than two days. &nbsp;Again, as has always been the case, in Primary and in EYFS, teacher absence will normally be covered by the year group team, supported by specialist teachers and members of the Leadership Team. &nbsp;In Secondary, class cover is arranged across the team with work set by the relevant Head of Department, or the absent teacher if they are able. &nbsp;We are also looking to recruit an additional Teaching Assistant to join our team on a supply basis, to further boost our cover capacity. &nbsp;Where we know about longer term or planned teacher absence, such as for training, that will be communicated to the relevant parties by a member of the team, or the teacher themselves.</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">I am also grateful this week for the staff and students’ response to the fire evacuation which happened at Breaktime on Wednesday. &nbsp;Whilst this fortunately turned out to be a fault on the system, it was initially a “real” situation to which our Security guards and fire marshals reacted impressively. &nbsp;Mr Hill, Head of Key Stage 3, is a former firefighter and officer with the London Fire Brigade and I am delighted that he is working with Mr Johnson and me, sharing his expertise so that we can be assured that our emergency protocols follow best practice.</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">Thank you to all who have expressed an interest in working to support the school through either of our parent groups. &nbsp;The first meetings are scheduled for 8:30 am during our September 12th coffee morning, alongside other parent information seminars. &nbsp;Please confirm your attendance to the coffee morning by next Friday 6th September to principal@britishschoolyangon.org. &nbsp;Agendas and RSVPs will be sent out separately for the individual meetings. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">Wishing you all a very happy weekend with your children, and to parents of our Year 11s, perhaps some conversations about those big dreams and ambitions…</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">Tor Del Federico</span><br style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34);">Principal&nbsp;</div><div style="margin: 0px;"><br></div></font></span></div><div style="text-align: left;"><p class="MsoNormal" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin-right: 0px; margin-left: 0px;"><font size="2" style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" style="">The British School Yangon</font></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); margin-right: 0px; margin-left: 0px;"><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" size="2">www.britishschoolyangon.org</font></p></div></div>]]></td>
